Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new Federal Reserve Board members gives people in America – and the U.S. Congress – the opportunity to reflect on the world's most important central bank and its future course.
The obvious, first question to be raised is: how was it possible for the Fed to miss its most important mandate — ensuring price stability — to such an extent?
That the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation indicates a fundamental failure.
Institutional self-examination is certainly called for now.
Yet while interest rate policy generates headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
Another major question is therefore whether they will use their immense power to advance climate or social policy.
For example, the Fed could refuse to lend to companies in the fossil fuel sector, could require banks to grant loans only to firms with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer credit toward desired alternatives.
In addition, they could decide to explicitly base their regulatory activities on the name of equality or ethnic justice, by prescribing to banks where and to whom loans are granted, who is hired and who is fired, and so on.
But before we turn to the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will or should take, it is first necessary to clarify the serious failure of the Fed.
In 2008, the U.S. government made a fateful decision: financial institutions could still largely obtain funds for risky investments through the sale of short-term, highly volatile debt securities, but swarms of new regulatory agencies would henceforth assess the riskiness of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook large chunks of the subprime mortgages in the bank balance sheets.
Yet over the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the regulatory army of the Fed has never once asked itself what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually hit in early 2020, the Fed discarded its "Never again" promises from 2008 and intervened to an even greater extent.
In March, it became clear that commercial banks were unable to act as intermediaries in the market for plain vanilla U.S. Treasury securities.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The market corrections would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been postponed for a long time.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed saved the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but it never happened.
In addition, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Federal Reserve and the U.S. Treasury had resisted the idea of increasing the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial sector rescue package—the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
Yet in 2020, one had introduced, among other things, an explicit lower bound for the prices of corporate bonds through the "Powell put."
The predictable reply to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury will simply put out any new fire with another round of money flooding.
The problem lies, of course, in the incentives that these strategies have created.
Why go through the trouble of using cash reserves or balance sheet slack for purchases at falling prices, providing liquidity, or treating a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will inevitably surpass all and take the profits.
Why would a company issue shares when it can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state will support the debt or help the company out of a jam, as was the case with the airlines?
Why hesitate as an investor when buying dubious securities, if their value is guaranteed during tough times by another "whatever it takes" promise from the Fed?
No wonder that America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will bear the losses during the next downturn.
Student loans, government bonds, and mortgages are piling up and waiting their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
Yet each new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put more money into rescue operations, and people will not have much fun with billions of newly printed money.
If the anticipated rescue packages do not materialize, we will wake up in a major fire – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, regulators and legislators at least recognized the moral hazard and were concerned that during good times investors would reap profits, while during bad times taxpayers would have to cover the losses.
In 2020, people only boasted about the rescue operations in self-congratulation.
Exactly the Fed, which in 2008 failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages just as little as the pandemic in 2020, and now wants to conduct stress tests regarding "climate risks," will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next national bankruptcy, or another disruptive event.
The Federal Reserve's regulators do not even ask about the mentioned events.
And although jargon such as "networks," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to define "systemic" risk, aside from it becoming a catch-all term that grants regulators sweeping powers.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to predict risks, accurately measure the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that massive debts can always be paid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always steps in to bail out mountains of debt during bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
Better regulation can bridge partisan divides.
The Left is right when it says that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit very few Americans.
However, she starts from the wrong cause.
An immense effort to comply with regulations presents a major obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is meaningless.
Regulatory provisions are either wise or foolish, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and requires regulatory authorities no prophetic skills.
The Fed scandalously blocked companies in the narrow banking and payment services sector that could contribute to fulfilling the financial needs of many people in America.
Before committing itself to the salvation of the planet and the rectification of injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it has fulfilled its fundamental duty of protecting the financial system.
